The concept of ''Biomedical Instruments'' has greatly evolved from simple instruments such as ''Thermometers'' and ''Stethoscopes'' into more sophisticated ''[[w:en:Magnetoencephalogram|Magnetoencephalograms]]'' and ''[[w:en:Magnetocardiography|Magnetocardiograms]]''. This is a natural response for the demand of medical professionals for accurate and reliable medical instruments. The number of medical instruments has grown to more than 10,000, and the complexity of these instruments has grown at the same pace.<ref>The Biomedical Engineering Handbook, Second Edition; Joseph D. Bronzino [Ed.], CRC Press, 2000</ref>
