{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic| name=Mermish| type=Language| features=Used by [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Merpeople|Merpeople]]| appearance=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Goblet of Fire|''Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire'']]}}
== Overview ==
'''''Mermish''''' is the language used by [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Merpeople|Merpeople]].
== Extended Description ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Beginner Spoiler}}
Heard in air, Mermish is thin and screechy, because Merpeople's vocal equipment is geared to the more viscous aquatic environment. In the thin stuff that is our air, the vibrating bits move far too fast, making the tone of their voices hurtful to human ears.
After the [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Major Events/Second Task|Second Task]] of the [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Major Events/Triwizard Tournament|Triwizard Tournament]], [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Albus Dumbledore|Professor Dumbledore]] speaks with the mer-Chieftainess to determine what had happened under the lake. It is mentioned at that time that Dumbledore knows possibly a thousand languages, including mermish.
== Analysis ==
== Questions == {{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Questions}}
# In [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Goblet of Fire/Chapter 25|''Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire'']], how does Harry understand the mermish message within the golden egg?
== Greater Picture ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Intermediate Spoiler}}
[[Category:Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter]]

{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic| name=Renervate| type=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic#Spells|Spell]] (Charm)| features=Revives the subject| appearance=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Half-Blood Prince/Chapter 26|''Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince'']]}}
== Overview ==
'''''Renervate''''' is a general revival spell, used when trying to resuscitate someone who has been left unconscious by magical means.
== Extended Description ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Beginner Spoiler}}
While at first glance, this seems to be a special version of [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Enervate|Enervate]], the charm that counters the effect of a [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Stupefy|Stun]] spell, in fact it seems to be used for more general resuscitation.
We see this spell used once: [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Harry Potter|Harry]] uses it to attempt to revive [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Albus Dumbledore|Professor Dumbledore]] after Dumbledore has succumbed to the potion guarding the locket in the lake. Harry has limited success.
== Analysis ==
== Questions == {{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Questions}}
== Greater Picture ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Intermediate Spoiler}}
[[Category:Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter]]

{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic| name=Tergeo| type=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic#Spells|Spell]] (Charm)| features=Cleaning charm| appearance=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Half-Blood Prince|''Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince'']]}}
== Overview ==
One of a number of cleaning charms, '''''Tergeo''''' seems to siphon fluids or dust off a surface.
== Extended Description ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Beginner Spoiler}}
In ''Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince'', Hermione uses this spell to remove blood from Harry's robes; later, she uses it to clean spilled ink off Ron's Dementor essay.
In ''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows'', Ron uses this to clean grease off a rag which he then gives to Hermione to wipe her eyes with, and later [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Harry Potter|Harry]] uses this spell to clean dust off pictures that he finds in [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Bathilda Bagshot|Bathilda Bagshot]]'s house.
This charm seems to be related in effect to [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Evanesco|Evanesco]] and [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Scourgify|Scourgify]].
== Analysis ==
== Questions == {{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Questions}}
== Greater Picture ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Intermediate Spoiler}}
[[Category:Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter]]

{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic| name=Transfiguration Today| type=Publication| features=Professional journal| appearance=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Prisoner of Azkaban|''Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban'']]}}
== Overview ==
'''''Transfiguration Today''''' seems to be a professional journal, read by the more advanced wizards interested in learning about new magical techniques.
== Extended Description ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Beginner Spoiler}}
It is mentioned that, when [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Harry Potter|Harry]] is staying at The Leaky Cauldron after blowing up his [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Marge Dursley|Aunt Marge]], there are elderly wizards sitting in the parlor, reading ''Transfiguration Today''.
In [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Severus Snape|Snape]]'s memories, in [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Deathly Hallows/Chapter 33|''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows'']], there is a scene where Snape is railing at [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Albus Dumbledore|Professor Dumbledore]] about what an awful student Harry is. Dumbledore is only giving Snape about half his attention; as he listens, he is reading ''Transfiguration Today''.
== Analysis ==
Just as there are mass-market periodicals like ''[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Witch Weekly|Witch Weekly]]'', ''[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/The Daily Prophet|The Daily Prophet]]'', and ''[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/The Quibbler|The Quibbler]]'', there must be more professional publications that are similar to our scientific journals. After all, magic is not static; we hear that [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Wolfsbane Potion|Wolfsbane Potion]] was invented recently by an uncle of [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Marcus Belby|Marcus Belby]], and there are other advances alluded to in various places. While the mass media will trumpet the existence of such advances, when they happen, the professional journal will go into detail as to how the effects are achieved. ''Transfiguration Today'' is clearly such a professional journal.
