==== setvbuf ====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cstdio>
int setvbuf( FILE *stream, char *buffer, int mode, size_t size );
</source>
}}

The function setvbuf() sets the buffer for ''stream'' to be ''buffer'', with a size of size. mode can be one of:

* _IOFBF, which indicates full buffering
* _IOLBF, which means line buffering
* _IONBF, which means no buffering

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/fflush|fflush]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/setbuf|setbuf]]

[[Category:C++ Programming|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

==== ungetc ====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cstdio>
int ungetc( int ch, FILE *stream );
</source>
}}

The function ungetc() puts the character ''ch'' back in ''stream''.

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/getc|getc]]<br>(C++ I/O) [[C++ Programming/Code/IO/Functions/putback|putback]]

[[Category:{{FULLBOOKNAME}}|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

==== sprintf ====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cstdio>
int sprintf( char *buffer, const char *format, ... );
</source>
}}

The sprintf() function is just like [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/printf|printf]](), except that the output is sent to ''buffer''. The return value is the number of characters written. For example:

<source lang=cpp>
char string[50];
int file_number = 0;         

sprintf( string, "file.%d", file_number );
file_number++;
output_file = fopen( string, "w" ); 
</source>

Note that sprintf() does the opposite of a function like [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/atoi|atoi]]() -- where [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/atoi|atoi]]() converts a string into a number, sprintf() can be used to convert a number into a string.

For example, the following code uses sprintf() to convert an integer into a string of characters:

<source lang=cpp>
char result[100];
int num = 24;
sprintf( result, "%d", num );  
</source>

This code is similar, except that it converts a floating-point number into an array of characters:

<source lang=cpp>
char result[100];
float fnum = 3.14159;
sprintf( result, "%f", fnum );
</source>

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/fprintf|fprintf]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/printf|printf]]<br>(Standard C String and Character) [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/atof|atof]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/atoi|atoi]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/atol|atol]]

[[Category:{{FULLBOOKNAME}}|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

