==== tmpfile ====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cstdio>
FILE *tmpfile( void );
</source>
}}

The function tmpfile() opens a temporary file with a unique filename and returns a pointer to that file. If there is an error, null is returned.

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/tmpnam|tmpnam]]

[[Category:{{FULLBOOKNAME}}|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

==== tmpnam ====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cstdio>
char *tmpnam( char *name );
</source>
}}

The tmpnam() function creates a unique filename and stores it in name. tmpnam() can be called up to '''TMP_MAX''' times.

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/tmpfile|tmpfile]]

[[Category:{{FULLBOOKNAME}}|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

==== vprintf, vfprintf, and vsprintf ====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cstdarg>
#include <cstdio>
int vprintf( char *format, va_list arg_ptr );
int vfprintf( FILE *stream, const char *format, va_list arg_ptr );
int vsprintf( char *buffer, char *format, va_list arg_ptr );
</source>
}}

These functions are very much like [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/printf|printf]](), [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/fprintf|fprintf]](), and [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/sprintf|sprintf]](). The difference is that the argument list is a pointer to a list of arguments. '''va_list''' is defined in cstdarg, and is also used by (Other Standard C Functions) [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/va_arg|va_arg]]().

For example:

<source lang=cpp>
void error( char *fmt, ... ) {
  va_list args;
  va_start( args, fmt );
  fprintf( stderr, "Error: " );
  vfprintf( stderr, fmt, args );
  fprintf( stderr, "\n" );
  va_end( args );
  exit( 1 );
}   
</source>

[[Category:C++ Programming|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

