===== atof =====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cstdlib>
double atof( const char *str );
</source>
}}

The function atof() converts str into a double, then returns that value. str must start with a valid number, but can be terminated with any non-numerical character, other than "E" or "e". For example,

<source lang=cpp>
x = atof( "42.0is_the_answer" ); 
</source>

results in x being set to 42.0.

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/atoi|atoi]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/atol|atol]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/strtod|strtod]]<br>(Standard C I/O) [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/sprintf|sprintf]]

[[Category:C++ Programming|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

===== atoi =====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cstdlib>
int atoi( const char *str );
</source>
}}

The atoi() function converts str into an integer, and returns that integer. ''str'' should start with a whitespace or some sort of number, and atoi() will stop reading from ''str'' as soon as a non-numerical character has been read. For example:

<source lang=cpp>
int i;
i = atoi( "512" );
i = atoi( "512.035" );
i = atoi( "   512.035" );
i = atoi( "   512+34" );
i = atoi( "   512 bottles of beer on the wall" ); 
</source>

All five of the above assignments to the variable ''i'' would result in it being set to 512.

If the conversion cannot be performed, then atoi() will return zero:

<source lang=cpp>
int i = atoi( " does not work: 512" );  // results in i == 0
</source>

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/atof|atof]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/atol|atol]]<br>(Standard C I/O) [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/sprintf|sprintf]]

[[Category:C++ Programming|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

{| class="wikitable" style="float: right;"
| Navigate '''[[Java Programming/UserInterface|User Interface]]''' topic:<span class="noprint">({{navbar|Java Programming/UserInterface/Topic|mini=1|nodiv=1}})</span>
