{{TProblem |
Four vehicles are traveling at constant speeds between sections X and Y (280 meters apart) with their positions and speeds observed at an instant in time.  An observer at point X observes the four vehicles passing point X during a period of 15 seconds.  The speeds of the vehicles are measured as 88, 80, 90, and 72 km/hr respectively.  Calculate the flow, density, time mean speed, and space mean speed of the vehicles.
}}

* [[Fundamentals of Transportation/Traffic Flow/Solution|Solution]]

[[Category:Fundamentals of Transportation Problems]]

===== atol =====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cstdlib>
long atol( const char *str );
</source>
}}

The function atol() converts ''str'' into a long, then returns that value. atol() will read from ''str'' until it finds any character that should not be in a long. The resulting truncated value is then converted and returned. For example,

<source lang=cpp>
x = atol( "1024.0001" ); 
</source>

results in x being set to 1024L.

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/atof|atof]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/atoi|atoi]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/strtod|strtod]]<br>(Standard C I/O) [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/sprintf|sprintf]]

[[Category:C++ Programming|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

