I think it would be better to break up the program more and have more explanation to it.  It would also be beneficial to differentiate between AWT, SWT, and Swing.

Also, GridBagLayouts are much better than the kind you are using.

== Clean up examples ==

The examples in the Long Examples section need to be cleaned up, both due to bugs and poor programming practices. The concepts of the examples is sound however.
# Doesn't access swing components only from the event dispatch thread. This can cause a deadlock.
# Uses string literals for determining component placement instead of constants from the layout manager ("East", "West"... instead of BorderLayout.EAST, BorderLayout.WEST etc.)
# Uses one agrigate listener that has to check which buttons were pushed. There should be one listener to handle the number buttons, one for the operations, one for special buttons.
## Also, doing "if (src == button1)" is error prone. If button1 has changed since the listener was added that will return false. 
# Formatting and naming convention doesn't follow Java standards. See [http://java.sun.com/docs/codeconv/html/CodeConventions.doc8.html#367 Java Coding Conventions]
# Two examples showing the same thing in functional and non-functional versions is overly verbose and confusing.
# String equality is done using var == "literal" instead of "literal".equals(var), this "works" only because all literals are inlined.
# "if (OperatorKey == true)" is redundant, should be "if(OperatorKey)"
# Status is set to literal values instead of being set to constant values. Set to "VALID", "FIRST", "ERROR" et al.
[[User:Dark Pegasus|Dark Pegasus]] 23:58, 14 October 2006 (UTC)

Applied changes. [[User:Dark Pegasus|Dark Pegasus]] 04:01, 16 October 2006 (UTC)

